\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The journey back up through the temple was slow. Demons lurked in every passage, above staircases, in the dark corners of rooms. One of these rooms was packed with man-wasps attempting to construct a hive. The bulbous structure would have been much too small for them if Mandri hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t cut each thorax in two. And by the light of his fire he saw the hive\u8217\'92s cladding material: compacted layers of regurgitated flesh, typical of the theme\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 demons run amuck. Not one step was made without hearing some distant thump or raging howl as demon ambushed demon. They tried to ambush Mandri, but he could see their Sparks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The Vessels directly behind shuffled along, short swords drawn, ganging up to kill whatever he missed. Their frazzled nerves testified to their desperation. This ascent would bring them out of danger, and to die now, after everything, would be the greatest tragedy.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Their extreme focus amused Mandri.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Why it amused him was a interesting question, but not one he could entertain because his senses were nearer his skin. There was an oddness to how his toes squeezed inside his shoes, how his palm tingled when he braced against the stonework, how his legs moved without apparent effort. Most strange was his breathing; the sound of it was unfamiliar, as if it were someone else\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s. All these stray sensations pushed him into an anxious malaise. It was a surreal experience when contrasted with the needs of the moment. He needed to be inside his eyes, searching the dark for demon Sparks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He dispatched an enthusiastic lizard demon. It was no keenkedrin, but it did have long teeth. He watched it curl up against his heat, then realized why the Vessel\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s extreme focus amused him\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 they feared completely different things than he did. Rightfully, they feared these demons. He feared his growling stomach. He needed to eat. Given recent events, that seemed like a very dangerous thing for him to do.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Then there was Ayram. The giant gripped his spud-bar spear a little too tightly. He walked a little too far behind, half-hiding behind cover, careful to keep as many bodies between him and Mandri as possible. His face was stuck in suspicion. And his was silence was loud enough. The giant did not say a word through the whole of the dark, not until they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d battled all the way up to the temple\u8217\'92s wide entrance hall. Solraheen\u8217\'92s golden mask still sat there atop the exit, inviting them outside. The Vessel\u8217\'92s rushed towards it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No one leaves,\u8221\'94 Ayram growled, stopping them all in their tracks.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They turned to face him, suddenly wondering if there was to be one last final battle, hoping Mandri was on their side.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93My dear giant,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, \u8220\'93This is not the place to idle.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram grunted. He walked to the body of the green robed prince, who still lay in the middle of the room. He poked around the ash pit with his long spear. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Someone light a fire,\u8221\'94 he growled.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We need to leave!\u8221\'94 Pyetle challenged. \u8220\'93We should put as much distance between us and this place as possible.\u8221\'94 motioned for his man with the torch.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Moto,\u8221\'94 Ayram said. \u8220\'93There\u8217\'92s wood in a pile. Fetch it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pytele. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93May I ask why you insist on lingering here?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram stared at Mandri. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We need to talk.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri licked his teeth and said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I know.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto tossed a few logs onto the ash pit. A Vessel lent his torchfire to it, and in a flash, it was firing. It had a sweet scent. had a fire. Ayram sat down next to the green robed prince. He bade Mandri to sit across from him, and Mandri did.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Anyone have anything to eat?\u8221\'94 Mandri asked. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle retrieved two small bricks of cappash from a Vessel. Cappash was a dried and minced lizard meat spiced with bitter herbs and caked in yellowed fat. He sat down on Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s right, then handed a cappash brick to Mandri. \u8220\'93You look like you need it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri accepted the offering. He nibbled on a corner, thinking there\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d be no taste. At first there wasn\u8217\'92t, but the second chew saw the meat\u8217\'92s smoky flavor percolate into being. Somehow the act of eating was centering him.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was not entirely enjoyable.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Sol\u8217\'92s light, I\u8217\'92m tired,\u8221\'94 he mumbled between mouthfuls. \u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t suppose we could take some time to sleep? Perhaps take turns?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto said as stole the other cappash brick out of Pyetle\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hand, then sat down on Mandri\u8217\'92s left. \u8220\'93I didn\u8217\'92t know a Mazid needs to eat,\u8221\'94 he said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s because he\u8217\'92s not a Mazid,\u8221\'94 Ayram said. \u8220\'93Not anymore. Schisol\u8217\'92s own shadow named him the Burshageet.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram paused to let the accusation breathe, because now that it was out the air it was its own kind of beast. It had horns. It to be dealt with.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I understand how you feel,\u8221\'94 Mandri said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93None of this matters,\u8221\'94 Moto said, dejected. \u8220\'93Let it all burn. We are }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 done}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram grunted. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93This will not be done until he is dead.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let\u8217\'92s all calm down,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, a little ruffled. \u8220\'93We are all on the same side.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You heard what the black witch said.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I do not consider her to be a trustworthy source of information.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Neither do I,\u8221\'94 Ayram said. \u8220\'93But her words needs accounting. His stomach growls. Look at him eat.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Do you want some?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram grimaced as though he were offered human flesh.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ve done nothing to deserve that look,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93If it weren\u8217\'92t for me, you\u8217\'92d be dead.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93May I suggest,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, \u8220\'93that we take stock of our situation? From where I sit, I see in Mandri a gift from Solraheen. I have faith that He\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Solraheen is dead,\u8221\'94 Ayram grumbled. \u8220\'93He has nothing to do with this.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then why does Mandri bear His fire? You all watched him turn back the hordes of Shis. Now you want to murder him for it?\u8221\'94 he leaned forward, suddenly convicted by his own argument. \u8220\'93He could kill you right this very moment, but he chooses not to! What crime has he committed?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 His question hung in the air unanswered, but Ayram was able to chew his way through this complication. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Give me a reason not to kill you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Scoff.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I feel like the fact that you\u8217\'92re still alive should be reason enough. And why assume that you could kill me? I don\u8217\'92t think you can. None of this matters anyways, because you won\u8217\'92t. You\u8217\'92re not going to kill me. Not tonight, at least. Perhaps tomorrow. I don\u8217\'92t know.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s disdain deepened. His face twisted up. \u8220\'93That black witch could see the future. She saw how her victory was assured}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 . }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She disemboweled herself for it! Why would she kill herself unless she was certain that }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 you }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 was going to finish her work!\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I see what\u8217\'92s happening here,\u8221\'94 Pyetle, shifting eagerly. \u8220\'93Your witch, the old woman who was flattened by that beast\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 excuse me, no disrespect, but she }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 was}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  flattened\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 she was seer, no?\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram nodded.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I imagine you became accustomed to her fortune telling. Now, she is no longer here. Without her direction, you are rudderless\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 again, no disrespect intended, but you }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 are}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  forcing us all to pause here on the doorstep of Shis so that you can determine what to do.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93All the gods are dead,\u8221\'94 Ayram. \u8220\'93That boy is the most powerful being in all the world. All the other Mazid have limits. He has none. I speak now about killing him, because the only being who can is himself.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The only way he dies now, is if he lets it happen. More than the fire, he has the sight. He can see the threads of fate. As well, he can cut them!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle astonished. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Is that what happened,\u8221\'94 remembering how the the demons were suddenly struck dumb down in the comet\u8217\'92s chamber. \u8220\'93Is what he says, true?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri saw threads. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It is,\u8221\'94 Mandri said, smiling in embarrassment of his power. \u8220\'93I can see a certain future. I do not see far, but I do see it.\u8221\'94 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And you can cut it?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri took Elrahet\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Black knife out of his robe.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He could see the threads and cut them easily, but wouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t a natural expression of will grow right back? And what about these thoughts of his, this desire to experiment? Perhaps even the idea of cutting a thread of fate was an inevitability drawn along a predictable curve through some hidden world to implant itself in his mind, forcing him to act.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 With this Black knife, could he cut away the act of cutting? Where was the thread which guided that action, and could he cut that, too? }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He watched in amazement as the knife and the hand holding it doubled, then tripled, then splayed out into a circular fan of hands holding knives, thousands of them, overlapping. Mandri twisted his wrist, and each blade turned. He saw, or thought he saw, a thin translucent web of threads connecting each blade to every other. He made to cut, to put this infinite regress of causes putting an end to their own infinite regress of effects. Only, none of them }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 could }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 cut; each edge slipped past their neighbor\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s thread and bent impossibly back around so as to cut their own, a recursive swirl which severed the very notion of comprehensibility.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Ayram,\u8221\'94 Mandri said, looking up. \u8220\'93Did Elrahet see this end?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93She did not tell me.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Well,\u8221\'94 Mandri mumbled, \u8220\'93If this all becomes too much I might seek you out. But I\u8217\'92ve got to try. I think that\u8217\'92s ultimately what she wanted.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 They spent the rest of the night watching the fire burn down to ash. There was a little conversation about what Pyetle was going to do, how he was going to carry news of these events back to Jeket. He wanted to take Mandri with him. Ayram was firmly against this, but he wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t for anything else.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri, for his part, stared into the fire and smiled. He smiled at how Pyetle saw in him something between a god and a long-lost brother, how Ayram wanted him dead, how Moto, still pining after his sister, hardly cared about him at all. It felt so incredible to mean such different things to different people. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think I\u8217\'92ll go back to Meskalim,\u8221\'94 Mandri said when the sun came up. \u8220\'93I want to do something about a nasty leech farm out there.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A leech farm!?\u8221\'94 Pyetle. \u8220\'93Mandri, there are more substantial things you could be doing. Come with me to Jeket and I will\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93I feel convicted. I\u8217\'92m going to do something about that damned farm.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But there\u8217\'92s\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93One thing at a time.\u8221\'94 Sighing at the realization of the monstrous task. \u8220\'93One thing at a time.\u8221\'94}}